// TEST: exec_self_return
// EXPECT: output "doubled=42;sum=63"
// EXPECT: targets js, python, rust
//
// Regression fixture for Q-self-subst (codegen-completeness P2): an impl block
// that writes `Self` in its OWN method signature.
//
// `Doubler.doubled(self) -> Self` writes `Self` in *return* position, and
// `Doubler.add(self, other: Self) -> Int` writes `Self` in *parameter*
// position. Before the checker fix, the impl method's own registered signature
// kept `Named("Self")` (only trait-declared method types were substituted), so
// both call sites hit E4001 (`Named("Self")` vs `Named("Doubler")`). The
// checker now substitutes `Self` -> the impl's target type across each impl
// method's params and return type at registration.
//
// Targets: js, python, rust emit and execute correct code (Rust lowers both
// positions to its native `Self`). ts and go are intentionally OMITTED — both
// have a *codegen* gap (separate workstream, not this pure-checker fix), each
// surfaced as an OPEN in this session's PR:
//   * Go renders a `TypeSelf` outside a *trait*-impl method as the
//     `/* Self */` placeholder (`bock-codegen/src/go.rs` only sets
//     `go_self_subst` when `use_value_receiver` is true), emitting an invalid
//     Go signature (missing return / param type).
//   * TS lowers `Self` to the `this` type, but the impl methods are assigned to
//     `Doubler.prototype = function(...): this { … }`; TS only permits a `this`
//     type inside a class/interface member, so `tsc` rejects it (TS2526).
// Both gaps are orthogonal to (and unblocked by) the checker fix.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale; not load-bearing here since go is omitted, but kept
// consistent with the other exec fixtures).
module main

record Doubler {
  value: Int
}

impl Doubler {
  fn doubled(self) -> Self {
    Doubler { value: self.value + self.value }
  }

  fn add(self, other: Self) -> Int {
    self.value + other.value
  }
}

fn main() -> Void {
  let d: Doubler = Doubler { value: 21 }
  let bigger: Doubler = d.doubled()
  let extra: Doubler = Doubler { value: 21 }
  println("doubled=${bigger.value};sum=${bigger.add(extra)}")
}
